---
import AnimatedHero from "../components/AnimatedHero.astro";
import MarketingShell from "../components/MarketingShell.astro";
---

<MarketingShell
  title="Code review that brings receipts"
  description="Warden is a local code review CLI that turns tool output, citations, and repository context into review comments you can audit."
>
  <main>
    <section class="hero-section">
      <div class="hero-copy">
        <p class="eyebrow">Local code review CLI</p>
        <h1>Warden</h1>
        <p class="hero-lede">
          Most AI reviewers ask you to trust a paragraph. Warden starts with the boring evidence:
          type errors, lint findings, dependency records, source snippets, and citations. The model
          only gets to turn that trail into a review a human can act on.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-actions">
          <a class="button primary" href="/docs/" data-astro-prefetch>Read docs</a>
          <a class="button secondary" href="/examples/" data-astro-prefetch>See output</a>
        </div>
      </div>
      <AnimatedHero />
    </section>

    <section class="proof-strip" aria-label="Review contract">
      <p><strong>Runs in your repo</strong><span>no hosted review backend</span></p>
      <p><strong>Checks before it writes</strong><span>tools and OSV before prose</span></p>
      <p><strong>Asks when unsure</strong><span>questions beat invented certainty</span></p>
      <p><strong>Returns a contract</strong><span>stable JSON for future wrappers</span></p>
    </section>

    <section class="home-band">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">The thesis</p>
        <h2>A reviewer should know what it can prove.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="feature-grid">
        <article>
          <span class="feature-kicker">01</span>
          <h3>The facts come first.</h3>
          <p>
            TypeScript, ESLint, duplication checks, dependency audit output, and repository snippets
            form the evidence layer. Warden can be useful only after that layer exists.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <span class="feature-kicker">02</span>
          <h3>External claims carry receipts.</h3>
          <p>
            Vulnerability claims are checked against OSV before they reach the final review. If a
            source cannot be checked, the claim should not survive.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <span class="feature-kicker">03</span>
          <h3>The output is built to travel.</h3>
          <p>
            The CLI is the first surface, not the last. Every run returns stable comments with ids,
            tiers, categories, sources, and degradation notes that other wrappers can render later.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="workflow-band">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Pipeline</p>
        <h2>Quiet machinery, readable review.</h2>
      </div>
      <ol class="workflow">
        <li><span>Detect</span><p>Find the workspace shape and the diff that actually needs review.</p></li>
        <li><span>Run</span><p>Execute the tools that can speak with mechanical confidence.</p></li>
        <li><span>Verify</span><p>Attach sources to claims that reach outside the codebase.</p></li>
        <li><span>Write</span><p>Let the model rank, clarify, and phrase the final comments.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section class="closing-band">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Design record</p>
        <h2>Personal tool, public craft bar.</h2>
        <p>
          Warden is being built for one person first, but not as a throwaway. The decisions are
          written down, the vocabulary is named, and the site stays static so it does not pretend to
          be a hosted product before the review engine earns that shape.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="closing-actions">
        <a class="button primary" href="/design/" data-astro-prefetch>Read design notes</a>
        <a class="button secondary" href="/notes/" data-astro-prefetch>Read notes</a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</MarketingShell>
